When I worked as a masseuse I first of all wore "professional" clothes to emphasize that I didn't use my trade as an euphemism for something else. Secondly, I refused any request to go to work late at night in a hotel room etc and I would NEVER go to sauna alone with my client, it simply isn't professional but gives just the kind of image we who take our work seriously try to avoid.* This guy, instead of packing his bags when feeling uncomfortable, went to sauna with him, and then invited Travolta touch him!!  I'm not saying that anyone has the right to molest another person regardless of situation but for crying out loud, either the masseur had no self-preservation instinct but this story does sound more like he tried to make a quick buck.
I was trained in Swedish massage, which originates from what now is Finland. There it was common for an older, married woman to come and wash people with brush and soap and massage was part of that washing routine.  No matter how hot the sauna would be, the washer woman would never take her clothes off! Equally, if I was to give a massage in a sauna, I would be fully clothed and only go into the washroom when called... It is normal for a person to be massaged to keep their underpants on but some clients that came into the school clinic, would insist of being naked: as an older woman I would take over those "difficult" clients to protect girls who were still in their 20's. Usually my regular clients were understanding about the swap.

Na M  "I'm usually skeptical when there is only one accusation, but almost inevitably, one accusation turns into five, and 5 turn into 20. Then there can really be no doubt. Guys who are total creeps usually don't just do it once."

Consider what you've written.  You converted "one accusation" into proof merely by citing proliferation of the original allegation.  That's exactly how every witch hunt and political show trial operates.  Somebody opens the proceedings and then others take the cue, piling on with similar charges- none of which makes any of it true. BTW, I believe they prefer to be called massage therapists, unless they are unlicensed.  Masseur and masseuse are considered less professional.  In Canada, they actually prefer to be called registered massage therapists because the governing body that registers them has exclusive legal use of the term "massage",  or massage therapy, so no one else is supposed to call themselves massage anything.  Calling yourself an RMT proves you are a professional.
